According to [this article][1] &quot;its not possible to pass arguments on the command line which can be used by that task&quot;.

That said, you can do something like this:

    const gulp = require(&quot;gulp&quot;);
    
    const copy = {
        first: {
            dest: &#39;dist/index.scala.html&#39;,
            src: &#39;app/index.scala.html&#39;
        },
        second: {
            dest: &#39;dist/setup.scala.html&#39;,
            src: &#39;app/setup.scala.html&#39;
        }
    };
    
    for (let key in copy) {
        gulp.task(&#39;copy:&#39; + key, cb =&gt; {
            console.log(&#39;copy[key]: &#39;, copy[key]);
            cb();
        });
    }

Note: I&#39;ve changed `copy = [`...`]` to `copy = {`...`}` because arrays can&#39;t have strings (such as &#39;first&#39;) as keys but objects can.

Then to run the gulp commands:

`gulp copy:first`

`gulp copy:second`

You may also want to have a look at [Pass Parameter to Gulp Task][2].


  [1]: https://www.sitepoint.com/pass-parameters-gulp-tasks/
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/28538918/pass-parameter-to-gulp-task

